-- ── EasyWI ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Easy-Wi is a free, open-source web interface for managing game servers, voice servers, and hosting infrastructure from a single control panel.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Open-source project maintained by an independent developer and community$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Leipzig, Germany$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Easy-Wi Review 2026: Game Server Panel Features$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Easy-Wi is a free, open-source web panel for managing game servers, voice servers, and hosting. Explore its features, setup, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Easy-Wi (styled as Easy-Wi Webinterface, and referred to on some directories as easy-wi or EasyWI) is a free, open-source, self-hosted web interface for managing game servers, voice servers, and general hosting infrastructure. It was created by developer Alexander Dörwald, based in Leipzig, Germany, and is distributed publicly through the easy-wi GitHub organization, where the core application lives in the easy-wi/developer repository alongside supporting packages for documentation and installation. The project positions itself as a middleware layer that sits between a web-based administrative interface and the actual server processes running on one or more physical or virtual machines, communicating with those machines over protocols such as SSH and RCON to start, stop, monitor, and configure services remotely.

The primary use case for Easy-Wi is game server hosting. A hosting provider, gaming community, clan, or individual running a small network of dedicated or virtual servers can use the panel to deploy and manage game servers for titles such as Counter-Strike, Minecraft, and Team Fortress, along with dozens of other supported games, from one centralized dashboard. Alongside game servers, the panel manages TeamSpeak 3 voice servers, and it includes webspace management features compatible with Apache2 and Nginx, plus database management for MySQL or MariaDB instances that can run independently or alongside a hosted website. A lightweight built-in content management system lets operators publish pages and news directly from the panel, which is useful for hosting providers who want a simple public-facing storefront or community page without deploying a separate CMS.

Operationally, Easy-Wi emphasizes automation to reduce the manual workload of running many game servers at once. Deployments use a symlink-based storage approach that significantly cuts installation time and disk usage compared to fully duplicating game files for every server instance, since shared base files are linked rather than copied. Services are continuously monitored, with automatic restart on crash, and updates to game or voice server software can be pushed centrally from an image server rather than patched on every machine individually. The interface itself is responsive, adapting to desktop and mobile screens, which matters for hosting providers and community admins who need to check server status or restart a crashed instance from a phone.

As an open-source project, Easy-Wi carries no licensing fee, subscription cost, or per-server charge from the software itself — the entire application, from the core web interface to the game-server automation scripts, is available at no cost through its GitHub repositories. There is no published commercial SaaS tier, hosted cloud version, or enterprise pricing page; anyone who wants to run Easy-Wi provides their own server infrastructure, whether that is a single machine for a small gaming clan or a distributed fleet of dedicated servers for a commercial hosting business. Because it is free and self-hosted, the realistic cost for an organization is the underlying server and bandwidth capacity needed to run the game and voice servers it manages, not the panel software itself.

Easy-Wi's target audience spans a wide range of technical sophistication: commercial game-hosting companies that need to provision and resell server capacity at scale, gaming communities and clans that want to self-manage their own Counter-Strike or Minecraft servers, LAN party organizers who need temporary server provisioning, and individual hobbyists running a personal game server for friends. The panel's documentation and interface are available in both English and German, reflecting the project's European, German-speaking origin, and an active Discord community supplements the GitHub-based support channel for troubleshooting and feature discussion.

In the game-server-panel category, Easy-Wi competes with other self-hosted and commercial control panels such as Pterodactyl, TCAdmin, Multicraft, and Open Game Panel. Compared to Pterodactyl, which has become a dominant modern choice built around Docker containerization, Easy-Wi takes an older, more traditional approach using direct SSH/RCON server management and symlink-based deployment rather than full containerization. This makes it lighter-weight in some respects but potentially less isolated between server instances than a container-native competitor. For hosting operators and communities who value a mature, free, actively available open-source panel with built-in CMS and voice-server support in one package, Easy-Wi remains a viable option, particularly among the German-speaking hosting community where it originated.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '9f50961f-98ec-4271-b1ef-2f486257a4a5';

