-- ── Eat App ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Eat App is a cloud-based restaurant reservation and table management platform that helps venues take online bookings, manage guest data, and run CRM and marketing campaigns.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium / Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Dubai, United Arab Emirates (originally founded in Manama, Bahrain)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Arabic$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Eat App Review 2026: Features, Pricing & Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Eat App is a restaurant reservation and table management platform. Compare its Free, Starter, Essential, and Pro pricing plans and key features here.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Eat App is a cloud-based restaurant reservation, table management, and guest CRM platform built for restaurants, hotels, and hospitality venues. The company was founded by Nezar Kadhem, originally in Bahrain, before relocating its headquarters to Dubai, United Arab Emirates, where the business now operates from offices in Jumeirah Lake Towers. Eat App has grown into a well-funded hospitality technology company, having raised a total of roughly $31.6 million across multiple funding rounds, including an $11 million round in 2022 led by Middle East Venture Partners (MEVP), 500 Startups, Derayah Venture Capital, and other regional investors, following an earlier $5 million round in 2020. That funding history reflects Eat App's positioning as one of the more established reservation platforms to emerge from the Middle East hospitality-tech scene, though it now serves restaurants across many international markets.

At a functional level, Eat App gives restaurants a single system for accepting reservations from multiple channels — the restaurant's own website, its Facebook and Instagram profiles, Google, and the Eat App partner network of consumer-facing booking sites — and consolidating them into one live view of table availability. The floor plan and table management module lets host staff visualize the dining room, seat walk-ins alongside pre-booked reservations, and manage a digital waitlist so guests without a reservation can be notified by text when their table is ready. Every reservation builds a guest profile in Eat App's built-in CRM, capturing visit history, dietary preferences, spend, and notes, which restaurant staff and marketing teams can use to personalize service and run targeted email or WhatsApp marketing campaigns to past guests. Eat App also offers dedicated mobile apps for iPhone and Android that let managers and hosts view and edit reservations, message guests, and monitor key metrics from the floor rather than being tied to a host stand terminal, and integrates with point-of-sale and phone (PBX) systems to enrich guest profiles with order and call history from other systems already in use at the venue.

Eat App's pricing follows a freemium-to-subscription structure with four public tiers plus a custom Enterprise option. The Free plan costs nothing and supports up to 100 covers per month, along with a chat inbox and custom booking forms and surveys, making it usable for small or newly opened venues. The Starter plan is priced at $99 per month billed monthly, or roughly $69 per month when billed annually, and raises the limit to 300 covers per month while adding 100 WhatsApp guest conversations and an email marketing suite. The Essential plan costs $199 per month monthly (about $159 per month billed annually) and removes the covers cap entirely, adding waitlist management, 250 WhatsApp conversations, and a loyalty program suite. The top public tier, Pro, is $389 per month monthly (about $299 per month annually), and includes unlimited covers, 500 WhatsApp conversations, every available add-on module, and a dedicated customer success manager. Annual billing across paid tiers saves customers roughly 30 percent compared to paying month to month. Restaurant groups and hotel chains needing centralized guest data across many locations, enterprise security controls, or custom integrations can move to a bespoke Enterprise plan priced through direct sales consultation. Add-on modules such as POS integration, phone system integration, prepayment and deposit collection, and an online waitlist widget can each be added individually on lower tiers for additional monthly fees, whereas the Pro plan bundles them in.

The platform's target users span independent restaurants, multi-location restaurant groups, hotel food and beverage outlets, and other reservation-driven hospitality venues that want to reduce no-shows, better manage peak-hour table turns, and build repeat business through guest data rather than relying on generic third-party reservation marketplaces. Competing products in this space include OpenTable, Resy, SevenRooms, and Tock, each of which similarly blends reservations, CRM, and marketing tools, though pricing models and target restaurant tiers vary — SevenRooms and Tock, for instance, are often associated with higher-end fine dining and nightlife venues, while OpenTable brings a large built-in diner network. Eat App differentiates itself with transparent, fixed monthly pricing and no per-cover or per-reservation fees, in contrast to marketplaces like OpenTable that have historically charged restaurants per-seated-diner fees on top of subscription costs — a distinction Eat App emphasizes heavily in its own marketing as a lower total cost of ownership for venues with high reservation volume.

Eat App requires no special installation since it runs entirely in the browser and through its companion mobile apps, and restaurants typically go live within days of signing up by connecting existing booking channels and importing guest history. Because reservation and guest data sits centrally within Eat App's CRM, restaurant groups can also use the platform to standardize service and marketing across multiple locations from one dashboard rather than managing each venue's guest relationships independently.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '58340ae3-bb72-49c9-8eb1-38e05b4918b4';

