-- ── ECC Tools ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$ECC Tools is an open-agent-harness system that analyzes a repository and generates project-specific skills, rules, and security checks for AI coding agents like Claude Code, Codex, and Cursor.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2026, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Solo founder-led project (Affaan Mustafa) with community contributors$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$ECC Tools Review 2026: Features, Pricing & Setup$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$ECC Tools generates skills, rules, and security checks for AI coding agents like Claude Code. Compare its Free, Pro, and Enterprise pricing plans.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$ECC Tools is a developer platform built around what its creator calls an open agent harness system for AI coding assistants such as Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, and OpenCode. It was created by developer Affaan Mustafa and, according to project materials, originated at a Claude Code hackathon hosted by Cerebral Valley and Anthropic in early 2026. The project grew quickly from an open-source repository into a broader commercial platform, and by mid-2026 press coverage described the underlying open-source ecosystem, informally referred to as Everything Claude Code, as having crossed well over 200,000 combined GitHub stars across its repositories, making it one of the more visible community projects in the fast-growing AI coding agent tooling space.

The core problem ECC Tools addresses is that AI coding agents, by default, have no persistent memory of a specific codebase's conventions, security requirements, or team workflows: every new agent session effectively starts from zero context. ECC Tools solves this by analyzing a repository's commit history, existing configuration files, and documentation, then generating reusable skills, rules, hooks, commands, and security policies tailored to that specific project. Rather than silently modifying a repository, the tool opens pull requests containing its suggested additions, so a human reviewer can accept, edit, or reject the generated configuration before it is merged — a design choice the project describes as reviewable automation.

ECC Tools is structured in layers. At the base is a free, MIT-licensed open-source repository containing a large library of pre-built skills, agents, and commands (261 skills, 64 agents, and 84 commands, according to project documentation) covering common workflows like planning, testing, code review, and continuous learning from a codebase over time. On top of that sits a hosted GitHub App that brings repo-native automation to both public and private repositories, letting teams trigger analysis and audits through issue-comment commands such as slash-ecc-tools-analyze, slash-ecc-tools-setup, and slash-ecc-tools-audit. A third component, AgentShield, is a dedicated security scanner for AI agent configurations, running around 100 static analysis rules against agent config files, MCP server definitions, and tool permissions to catch injection risks and misconfigurations before they reach production, and it can optionally run a red-team, blue-team, and auditor pipeline using multiple AI models to simulate adversarial attacks against an agent's guardrails.

Pricing follows a three-tier freemium model. The Free tier applies to public repositories only, allowing up to 10 analyses per month with a limit of 200 commits scanned per run, along with issue-comment-triggered pull requests and community support, and requires no credit card. The Pro tier costs $19 per active developer seat per month, or $190 per seat billed yearly (roughly a 17% discount versus monthly), and unlocks private repository analysis, PR-triggered audits, 50 analyses per seat, 1,000 commits per run, AgentShield-backed configuration scanning, automatic triggers on large pushes and pull requests, self-serve billing, and priority email support. The Enterprise tier is custom-priced and scoped per organization, offering unlimited analyses, 5,000 commits per run, single sign-on-ready governance and audit logging, custom rule and policy packs, dedicated onboarding, and service-level agreements for organization-wide rollouts.

ECC Tools targets engineering teams and larger organizations adopting AI coding agents at scale who need consistent development conventions, faster onboarding of new contributors into agent-assisted workflows, and a security review layer specifically built for the emerging risks around agent configuration and tool permissions, rather than traditional application code vulnerabilities. Because it works across multiple agent harnesses — including Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, and OpenCode — rather than locking a team into a single vendor's agent, it appeals to teams that use more than one AI coding tool and want consistent skills and security policies applied across all of them. The project lists enterprise-oriented sponsors including CodeRabbit and Greptile, both of which operate in the adjacent AI code review space.

Within the fast-moving AI developer tooling category, ECC Tools is best understood as sitting at the intersection of two emerging product types: agent context/skill management (competing conceptually with built-in project memory and rules features that individual agent vendors are adding natively) and AI agent security scanning (competing with dedicated tools focused specifically on securing MCP servers and agent tool permissions). Its key differentiator is combining both concerns — generating useful project context for agents and auditing the security posture of that same agent configuration — inside one reviewable, pull-request-based workflow, built on top of a large, freely available open-source skills library rather than requiring teams to build their own from scratch.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'b66550cc-ba3f-493f-afe3-06c11c362355';

