-- ── eClinicalWorks ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$eClinicalWorks is a leading privately held cloud electronic health record and practice management platform used by hundreds of thousands of physicians across the United States.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$449/month per provider$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1999, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$5,000+ employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Westborough, Massachusetts, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$eClinicalWorks Review 2026: EHR Features & Pricing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$eClinicalWorks is a leading cloud EHR and practice management platform. Compare its pricing, features, and alternatives for medical practices in 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$eClinicalWorks is a cloud-based electronic health record (EHR) and practice management platform founded in 1999 in Westborough, Massachusetts, by Girish Navani, who continues to serve as CEO and president, alongside a small group of co-founders. Navani has said the idea for the company was sparked by attending a technology conference in 1999 where a presentation on the future of the wireless industry made clear that healthcare was lagging far behind other sectors in adopting digital tools, and he set out to rid physician offices of paper records and connect providers electronically to pharmacies, labs, and the rest of the healthcare supply chain. More than two decades later, eClinicalWorks has grown into the largest privately held ambulatory EHR vendor in the United States, reporting that its software is used by more than 850,000 physicians across over 180,000 facilities, and the company reported 2024 revenues of approximately $900 million while remaining privately held and consistently profitable rather than pursuing an IPO.

The platform covers the core software needs of an outpatient medical practice: an electronic health record for clinical documentation, e-prescribing with formulary checking, a patient portal, secure messaging between patients and providers through eClinicalMessenger, document and referral management, and a mobile companion app called eClinicalMobile that lets physicians access charts and interact with patients away from the office. eClinicalWorks also offers eClinicalWorks P2P, a peer-to-peer health information exchange feature, and eBO View for business intelligence and reporting, alongside registry reporting tools that help practices meet regulatory quality-reporting requirements. In 2023, the company released its current-generation V12 platform, described as its most significant architectural overhaul to date, which introduced a redesigned clinical workflow engine, deeper AI integration through a virtual assistant called Eva, and expanded interoperability through a data-exchange initiative called PRISMA, reflecting the broader EHR industry's push toward AI-assisted clinical documentation and cross-system data sharing.

Pricing is structured around a small number of straightforward, publicly quoted tiers rather than the highly customized enterprise-sales pricing common among hospital-system EHR vendors. The EHR Only plan costs $449 per provider per month and includes the electronic health record, eClinicalMobile, eClinicalWorks P2P, the patient portal, eClinicalMessenger, document and referral management, meaningful-use dashboards, eBO View reporting, registry reporting, e-prescribing, and 24x7 support, maintenance, cloud hosting, and disaster recovery, along with unlimited access to the company's training webinars. Practices that also need billing and scheduling software can step up to EHR with Practice Management at $599 per provider per month, which adds a full practice management module and billing implementation services on top of everything in the EHR Only tier. For practices that would rather outsource billing entirely, eClinicalWorks offers Revenue Cycle Management as a Service, priced at 2.9% of practice collections rather than a flat monthly fee, which bundles claims creation and processing, denial and rejection management, appeals handling, and ongoing accounts-receivable visibility together with the same EHR feature set. The company states there are no start-up costs on any of the three plans.

eClinicalWorks' target customers span the full range of ambulatory care: solo and small-group physician practices, larger multi-specialty medical groups, federally qualified health centers, urgent care clinics, and behavioral health practices, all of which need certified EHR software to meet regulatory requirements, participate in value-based care programs, and bill insurers electronically. Because pricing scales per provider rather than requiring a large upfront enterprise contract, the platform is accessible to small independent practices in a way that hospital-oriented systems such as Epic often are not, while still offering enough depth in practice management and revenue-cycle services to serve larger multi-location groups.

A notable part of eClinicalWorks' public history is a 2017 settlement with the U.S. Department of Justice, in which the company paid $155 million to resolve allegations that it had falsely obtained federal certification for its EHR software under the Office of the National Coordinator's (ONC) certification program, among other allegations related to the federal Meaningful Use incentive program. As part of the settlement, eClinicalWorks entered into a five-year Corporate Integrity Agreement with the HHS Office of Inspector General, which the company has since completed. The episode is frequently referenced in evaluations of the company because it remains one of the largest EHR-related False Claims Act settlements in U.S. healthcare history, though it has not prevented the company from continuing to grow into the market-leading position it holds among ambulatory practices today.

In the competitive EHR landscape, eClinicalWorks is most often compared with Epic, Athenahealth, NextGen Healthcare, Practice Fusion, and Cerner (now Oracle Health), among others. Epic dominates large hospital systems and academic medical centers with a comprehensive but expensive and complex platform, whereas eClinicalWorks has built its position primarily in the ambulatory and outpatient practice segment, competing more directly with Athenahealth and NextGen for small-to-midsize physician groups. Its main differentiators are straightforward per-provider pricing without large upfront enterprise costs, an especially large installed base among independent and small-group practices, and a broad bundled feature set — patient portal, messaging, mobile access, and reporting — included in the base EHR price rather than sold as separate add-on modules.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'abea60cc-5f26-45e3-9696-3dec899a6984';

