-- ── Ecwid ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Ecwid by Lightspeed is a cloud ecommerce platform that lets merchants add an online store to an existing website, social media page, or marketplace without rebuilding their site.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$5/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2009, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Part of Lightspeed Commerce Inc. (NYSE: LSPD, publicly traded)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Montreal, Quebec, Canada (originally founded in Ulyanovsk, Russia)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Russian$q$, $q$Japanese$q$, $q$Chinese$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Ecwid by Lightspeed Review 2026: Pricing & Features$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Ecwid by Lightspeed is a cloud ecommerce platform starting at $5/month. Compare its Starter, Venture, Business, and Unlimited plans and key features.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Ecwid, now operating under the name Ecwid by Lightspeed, is a cloud-based ecommerce platform founded in 2009 by software engineers Ruslan Fazlyev and Yury Zaytsev. The company's name is a contraction of e-commerce widget, reflecting its original core idea: rather than forcing a merchant to build an entirely new website to sell online, Ecwid would provide a storefront widget that could be embedded into any existing website, blog, or social media page. Fazlyev had already built an earlier ecommerce product called X-Cart in 2001, and drew on that experience when launching Ecwid as a more flexible, embeddable alternative. The company was originally developed in Ulyanovsk, Russia, formally incorporated in October 2011, and opened a satellite office in Mountain View, California in early 2012 to support its growing US customer base. In 2021, Ecwid was acquired by Lightspeed Commerce, a publicly traded Canadian point-of-sale and ecommerce company (NYSE: LSPD), and the business has since become integrated into the Lightspeed family of products, with operations now centered around Lightspeed's Montreal, Quebec headquarters while continuing to operate the Ecwid brand and product.

The defining product idea behind Ecwid — a storefront that plugs into an existing site rather than replacing it — remains its core differentiator today, even as the platform has grown into a full-featured ecommerce system in its own right. Merchants can embed an Ecwid store directly into an existing WordPress, Wix, Squarespace, or custom-built website, sell through Instagram and Facebook shops, list products on marketplaces, and manage everything from one central Ecwid dashboard regardless of how many different storefronts display those products. This multi-channel-from-one-catalog approach appeals particularly to small businesses and existing website owners who don't want to migrate away from a site they've already built and optimized, distinguishing Ecwid from platforms like Shopify or BigCommerce that expect a merchant to build their entire site on the platform itself.

Ecwid's pricing consists of four published subscription tiers, all billed either monthly or annually (with a roughly 16% discount for paying annually). The Starter plan costs $5 per month and supports up to 10 products, more than 70 storefront templates, a default Ecwid subdomain, and email support, making it usable for very small catalogs or side projects. The Venture plan costs $35 per month ($29 per month billed annually) and raises the product limit to 100, while adding native Instagram and Facebook selling, a mobile management app, live chat, access to the Ecwid App Market, automated tax calculation, custom checkout, and sales reporting. The Business plan, at $65 per month ($49 per month annually), supports up to 2,500 products and adds marketplace selling integrations, subscription/recurring billing support, two staff accounts, phone support, abandoned cart recovery emails, wholesale pricing tiers, multi-lingual storefronts, and expanded promotion tools. The top tier, Unlimited, costs $149 per month ($119 per month annually) and removes the product cap entirely, adds point-of-sale integration for in-person selling, unlimited staff accounts, priority support, and a much larger allotment of promotional campaigns. Across every tier, Ecwid charges no setup fees and no transaction fees on sales, and every plan includes unlimited bandwidth and storage regardless of catalog size.

Ecwid provides native mobile apps for both iOS and Android that let merchants manage orders, inventory, and store settings from a phone, and a documented API is available for developers who want to build custom integrations or headless storefronts on top of the Ecwid backend. New users can try the platform through a free trial period before committing to a paid subscription, giving small business owners a way to test the embedded-storefront workflow against their existing site before paying.

Ecwid's target customers are primarily small and medium-sized businesses that already have an established website, blog, or social media presence and want to add ecommerce functionality without a full site rebuild, as well as brick-and-mortar retailers looking to add online and multi-channel selling alongside an in-person point-of-sale system — a natural fit given Lightspeed's own core business in retail and restaurant point-of-sale software. Since the 2021 acquisition, Ecwid customers have also gained a more direct path to Lightspeed's broader POS ecosystem for retailers who want unified in-store and online inventory management.

In the ecommerce platform category, Ecwid competes most directly with Shopify, BigCommerce, Squarespace Commerce, and WooCommerce. Its clearest differentiation from Shopify and BigCommerce is architectural: rather than requiring a merchant to build their entire online presence inside the platform, Ecwid is designed to be embedded into a site the merchant already has, which appeals to businesses that have invested significant time and SEO equity into an existing WordPress or Squarespace site and don't want to migrate. Combined with its lower entry-level price point of $5 per month, no transaction fees on any plan, and now the backing of a publicly traded parent company in Lightspeed, Ecwid positions itself as a lower-friction, lower-cost way for small merchants to sell online without abandoning an existing web presence.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '37d9ac64-b7a8-413c-8a11-4db621fc9e33';

